'''ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱ ᱯᱨᱚᱠᱟᱥ ᱵᱷᱚᱜᱚᱛ'''<ref>{{Cite web|title=Chetan Bhagat tweets his CBSE Class 10 mark sheet|url=https://www.educationworld.in/chetan-bhagat-tweets-his-cbse-class-10-mark-sheet/|date=3 August 2019|website=EducationWorld|access-date=25 May 2020}}</ref> (ᱡᱟᱱᱟᱢ ᱒᱒ ᱚᱯᱨᱮᱞ ᱑᱙᱗᱔) ᱫᱚ ᱥᱤᱧᱚᱛᱤᱭᱟ. ᱚᱱᱚᱞᱤᱭᱟ., ᱠᱟ.ᱦᱱᱤ ᱢᱟᱞᱟᱠᱟᱨ, [[ᱵᱚᱞᱤᱣᱩᱰ]] ᱥᱨᱤᱱ ᱨᱟᱭᱴᱚᱨ, ᱥᱳᱥᱤᱭᱟᱞ ᱢᱮᱰᱤᱭᱟ ᱤᱱᱯᱷᱩᱭᱮᱱᱥᱚᱨ(social media influencer) ᱟᱨ ᱢᱳᱴᱤᱵᱮᱥᱚᱱᱟᱞ ᱯᱷᱳᱠᱚᱨ(motivational speaker) ᱠᱟᱱᱟᱭ ᱾ ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱ ᱫᱚ ᱒᱐᱑᱐ ᱨᱮ [[ᱴᱟᱭᱤᱢ ᱢᱟᱜᱟᱡᱤᱱ]] ᱯᱟᱦᱴᱟ ᱠᱷᱚᱱ ᱥᱟᱯᱲᱟᱣ ᱞᱮᱱ ᱡᱮᱜᱮᱛ ᱨᱮᱱ ᱑᱐᱐ ᱜᱚᱴᱟᱝ ᱡᱟ.ᱥᱛᱤ ᱤᱱᱯᱷᱞᱩᱭᱮᱱᱥᱤᱭᱟᱞ(Influential) ᱦᱚᱲ ᱠᱚ ᱛᱟᱞᱟᱨᱮ ᱠᱚ ᱫᱚᱲᱚᱢ ᱞᱮᱫᱮᱭᱟ ᱾<ref name=Time>{{cite web |title=The 2010 TIME 100 |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/completelist/0,29569,1984685,00.html |website=Time |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>

ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱ ᱵᱷᱚᱜᱚᱛ [[ᱤᱱᱰᱤᱭᱟᱱ ᱤᱱᱥᱴᱤᱪᱭᱩᱴ ᱚᱯᱷ ᱢᱮᱠᱱᱳᱞᱳᱡᱤ|ᱟᱭ.ᱟᱭ.ᱴᱩ.]], ᱫᱤᱞᱞᱤ ᱠᱷᱚᱱ ᱢᱮᱠᱟᱱᱤᱠᱟᱞ ᱤᱸᱡᱤᱱᱤᱭᱚᱨᱤᱝ ᱨᱮ ᱵᱤ.ᱴᱮᱠ ᱰᱤᱜᱽᱨᱤ ᱦᱟᱛᱟᱣ ᱞᱮᱫᱟ ᱟᱨ [[ᱤᱱᱰᱤᱭᱟᱱ ᱤᱱᱥᱴᱤᱪᱭᱩᱴ ᱚᱯᱷ ᱢᱮᱱᱮᱡᱽᱢᱮᱸᱴ|ᱟᱭ.ᱟᱭ.ᱮᱢ.]], ᱚᱦᱚᱢᱚᱫᱟᱵᱟᱫᱽ ᱠᱷᱚᱱᱟᱜ ᱮᱢ.ᱵᱤ.ᱮ. ᱠᱚᱨᱟᱣ ᱞᱮᱫᱟ ᱾ ᱢᱤᱫ ᱤᱱᱵᱷᱮᱥᱴᱢᱮᱸᱴ ᱵᱮᱸᱠ ᱠᱷᱚᱱᱟᱜ ᱟᱡᱟᱜ ᱪᱟ.ᱠᱨᱤ ᱡᱤᱭᱚᱱ ᱮ ᱮᱦᱚᱵ ᱞᱮᱫ-ᱟ ᱾ ᱛᱚᱵᱮ ᱚᱱᱚᱞᱤᱭᱟ. ᱵᱮᱱᱟᱣ ᱥᱟᱱᱟᱭᱮ ᱠᱷᱟ.ᱛᱤᱨ ᱚᱱᱟ ᱪᱟ.ᱠᱨᱤ ᱵᱟ.ᱜᱤᱟᱫ-ᱟᱭ ᱾ ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱ ᱤᱨᱟ.ᱞ ᱜᱚᱴᱮᱡ ᱱᱳᱵᱮᱞ,ᱯᱮᱭᱟ ᱱᱚᱱ-ᱯᱷᱤᱠᱥᱚᱱ ᱯᱚᱛᱚᱵ-ᱮ ᱚᱞ ᱟᱠᱟᱫ-ᱟ ᱾ ᱟᱡᱟᱜ ᱡᱷᱚᱛᱚ ᱠᱷᱚᱱᱟᱜ ᱧᱩᱛᱩᱢᱟᱱ ᱯᱚᱛᱚᱵ [[ᱯᱷᱟᱭᱤᱵᱽ ᱯᱚᱭᱮᱸᱴ ᱥᱚᱢᱣᱟᱱ]] ᱫᱚ ᱒᱐᱐᱔ ᱨᱮ ᱨᱤᱞᱤᱡᱽ ᱞᱮᱱ ᱛᱟᱭᱟ ᱾ ᱟᱡᱟᱜ ᱯᱚᱛᱚᱵ ᱫᱚ ᱟᱭᱢᱟ ᱜᱮ ᱪᱟᱢᱯᱷᱮᱞ ᱮᱱᱟ ᱾ ᱚᱱᱟᱛᱮ ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱ ᱵᱷᱚᱜᱟᱛ ᱫᱚ "ᱡᱟ.ᱥᱛᱤ ᱟ.ᱠᱷᱨᱤᱧ ᱟᱠᱟᱱ ᱥᱤᱧᱚᱛ ᱨᱮᱭᱟᱜ ᱤᱝᱞᱤᱥ ᱱᱳᱵᱮᱞ ᱚᱱᱚᱞᱤᱭᱟ."‌ ᱠᱚ ᱢᱮᱛᱟᱦᱟᱭᱟ ᱾<ref>{{Cite web|title=A Conversation with Chetan Bhagat, the biggest selling English language novelist in India’s history.|url=https://thoughteconomics.com/|last=MBE|first=Vikas Shah|date=31 May 2019|website=Thought Economics|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> ᱡᱟᱦᱟᱸᱭᱮᱱ ᱜᱮ, ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱᱟᱜ ᱚᱱᱚᱞ ᱯᱚᱛᱚᱵ ᱠᱚ ᱫᱚ ᱟᱭᱢᱟ ᱦᱚᱲ ᱟ.ᱰᱤ ᱛᱮᱫ ᱜᱮ ᱠᱚ ᱞᱟᱱᱫᱟ ᱚᱴᱟᱝ-ᱟ, ᱠᱤᱪᱷᱩ ᱫᱚ ᱠᱚ ᱢᱮᱱ-ᱟ ᱵᱷᱟ.ᱜᱤ ᱞᱮᱠᱟ ᱚᱞ ᱵᱟᱭ ᱵᱟᱰᱟᱭ ᱟᱨ ᱠᱤᱪᱷᱩ ᱫᱚ ᱠᱚ ᱢᱮᱱ-ᱟ ᱡᱮᱢᱚᱱ ᱨᱚᱱᱚᱲ ᱠᱚ ᱞᱮᱠᱟᱛᱮ ᱥᱮ ᱥᱟᱶᱦᱮᱫ ᱠᱚ ᱞᱮᱠᱟᱛᱮ ᱚᱞ ᱵᱟᱭ ᱵᱟᱰᱟᱭᱟ ᱾<ref>{{Cite web|title=Why I gave Chetan Bhagat the 'nastiest review'|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/chetan-bhagat-one-indian-girl-catcher-in-the-rye-open-novelist-toi-feminism/story/1/13537.html|website=dailyo.in|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> ᱪᱮᱛᱚᱱ ''[[ᱣᱟᱱ ᱤᱱᱰᱤᱭᱟᱱ ᱜᱟᱞ|<nowiki/>'One Indian Girl'<nowiki/>]]'' ᱯᱚᱛᱚᱵ ᱦᱚᱸ ᱟ.ᱰᱤᱜᱮ ᱦᱚᱲ ᱠᱟ ᱠᱩᱥᱤᱭᱟᱫ ᱛᱟᱦᱮᱸᱫ ᱾<ref>{{Cite web|title=Chetan Bhagat accused of plagiarising his latest bestseller, One Indian Girl|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/books/chetan-bhagat-accused-of-plagiarising-his-latest-bestseller-one-indian-girl/story-1DLX2bx5PYZQQdGmhFUekK.html|date=25 April 2017|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Sales of Chetan Bhagat’s ‘One Indian Girl’ stopped by injunction, on plagiarism charges|url=https://scroll.in/latest/835550/chetan-bhagats-one-indian-girl-ordered-out-of-bookstores-on-plagiarism-charges|website=Scroll.in|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref>

In April 2017, a controversy erupted over a decision of [[University of Delhi|Delhi University]] to include Bhagat's novel ''[[Five Point Someone|<nowiki/>'Five Point Someone'<nowiki/>]]'' as part of the English Literature syllabus from the academic session that would start in July 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Chetan Bhagat’s Five Point Someone in Delhi University English literature syllabus|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi/chetan-bhagat-s-five-point-someone-in-delhi-university-english-literature-syllabus/story-JVRGnIQX5C7oGkaLnfysIN.html|date=24 April 2017|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Chetan Bhagat's Five Point Someone To Be Part Of DU's English Literature Syllabus|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/chetan-bhagats-five-point-someone-to-be-part-of-dus-english-literature-syllabus/298646|website=outlookindia.com/|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Five Point Someone in DU syllabus: Let’s stop blaming Chetan Bhagat and start rueing the state of Indian readership|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/web-edits/delhi-university-english-five-point-someone-in-du-syllabus-lets-stop-blaming-chetan-bhagat-and-start-rueing-the-state-of-indian-readership/|date=25 April 2017|website=The Indian Express|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> But after a lot of heated debate on this issue, the Delhi University decided in September 2017 to put on hold the recommendations of its English Department to include Bhagat's novel in their course and set up a review committee.<ref>{{Cite web|title='Five Point Someone' not part of DU curriculum this session|url=http://www.millenniumpost.in/delhi/five-point-someone-not-part-of-du-curriculum-this-session-263547|last=MP|first=Team|date=24 September 2017|website=millenniumpost.in|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=DU’s Proposal To Add 'Five Point Someone' in Curriculum Reconsidered|url=https://www.careerindia.com/news/delhi-university-proposal-to-add-five-point-someone-reconsidered-020712.html|last=Malavikka|date=25 September 2017|website=careerindia.com|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> Five of Chetan Bhagat's novels have been adapted into Bollywood films like ''<nowiki/>'[[Hello (2008 film)|Hello'<nowiki/>]]'' in 2008 ([[One Night @ the Call Center]]); ''[[3 Idiots|<nowiki/>'3 Idiots'<nowiki/>]]'' in 2009 ([[Five Point Someone]]); ''[[Kai Po Che!|<nowiki/>'Kai Po Che'<nowiki/>]]'' in 2013 ([[The 3 Mistakes of My Life]]); [[2 States (2014 film)|'2 States']] in 2014 ([[2 States: The Story of My Marriage|2 States]]); and ''[[Half Girlfriend (film)|<nowiki/>'Half Girlfriend'<nowiki/>]]'' in 2017 ([[Half Girlfriend]]). Bhagat has also done scriptwriting for Bollywood films like ''[[Kai Po Che!|<nowiki/>'Kai Po Che'<nowiki/>]]'' (2013) (based on his novel [[The 3 Mistakes of My Life]]); ''[[Kick (2014 film)|<nowiki/>'Kick'<nowiki/>]]'' (2014) and ''[[Half Girlfriend (film)|<nowiki/>'Half Girlfriend'<nowiki/>]]'' (2017) (based on his novel of the same name).<ref>{{Cite web|title=Every time Chetan Bhagat made it to Bollywood – A Bollywood Hit!|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/every-time-chetan-bhagat-made-it-to-bollywood/a-bollywood-hit/slideshow/63829137.cms|website=The Economic Times|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> Bhagat along with Pubali Chaudri, Supratik Sen and Abhishek Kapoor won the [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare Award]] for Best Screenplay for [[Kai Po Che!|'Kai Po Che!']] at the [[59th Filmfare Awards]] in January 2014. They are listed on the official website of Filmfare in 'Filmfare winners of the year 2014'.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Filmfare Awards Winners From 1953 to 2020|url=https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards/winners|website=filmfare.com|language=en|access-date=2020-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Filmfare Awards (2014)|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000245/2014/1/|publisher=IMDb|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> 

Bhagat is regularly invited as a Motivational Speaker by various institutes and organisations in India and abroad.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Speech By Chetan Bhagat At Symbiosis.. Complete Thread List – [Queries] / [Cases] / [Discussions] / [Updates]|url=https://www.citehr.com/224681-speech-chetan-bhagat-symbiosis.html|website=citehr.com|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Chetan Bhagat – London Speaker Bureau Asia|url=https://www.londonspeakerbureauasia.com/speakers/chetan-bhagat/|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> He is also a keen and influential social media enthusiast who shares his thoughts on current issues actively, especially on Twitter and Facebook where he has garnered a combined following of more than 18 million followers. He also writes op-ed columns for English and Hindi newspapers, including ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Times of India]]'' and ''[[Dainik Bhaskar]]'', focusing on youth, career, leadership, political issues and current affairs.
